children.comment: Everything in Dart is an [Object].
children.name: Object

children.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all [Object]s is to return true if and
only if [:this:] and [other] are the same object.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override
the [hashCode] method as well to maintain consistency.
Returns a string representation of this object.
children.name: toString

children.comment:
[noSuchMethod] is invoked when users invoke a non-existant method
on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the
invocation are passed to [noSuchMethod] in an [Invocation].
If [noSuchMethod] returns a value, that value becomes the result of
the original invocation.

The default behavior of [noSuchMethod] is to throw a
[noSuchMethodError].
children.name: noSuchMethod

children.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the
same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality
operator [:==:]. Other than that there are no guarantees about
the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and
there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides [hashCode] it should override the
equality operator as well to maintain consistency.
children.name: hashCode

children.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.
children.name: runtimeType

children.comment:
Creates a new [Object] instance.

[Object] instances have no meaningful state, and are only useful
through their identity. An [Object] instance is equal to itself
only.
children.name: Object

children.comment:
The [Iterator] class provides methods to iterate over an object. It
is transparently used by the for-in construct to test for the end
of the iteration, and to get the elements.

If the object iterated over is changed during the iteration, the
behavior is unspecified.

The [Iterator] is initially positioned before the first element. Before
accessing the first element the iterator must thus be advanced ([moveNext])
to point to the first element. If there is no element left, then [moveNext]
returns false.

A typical usage of an [Iterator] looks as follows:

    var it = obj.iterator;
    while (it.moveNext()) {
      use(it.current);
    }
children.name: Iterator

children.comment:
Moves to the next element. Returns true if [current] contains the next
element. Returns false, if no element was left.

It is safe to invoke [moveNext] even when the iterator is already
positioned after the last element. In this case [moveNext] has no effect.
children.name: moveNext

children.comment:
Returns the current element.

Return [:null:] if the iterator has not yet been moved to the first
element, or if the iterator has been moved after the last element of the
[Iterable].
children.name: current

children.comment:
The server initiates the handshake after the client connects,
so a request will never be created.
children.name: createRequest

children.comment:
After receiving the handshake packet, if all is well, an [AuthHandler]
is created and returned to handle authentication.

Currently, if the client protocol version is not 4.1, an
exception is thrown.
children.name: processResponse

children.comment:
Each command which the mysql protocol implements is handled with a [Handler] object.
A handler is created with the appropriate parameters when the command is invoked
from the connection. The transport is then responsible for sending the
request which the handler creates, and then parsing the result returned by 
the mysql server, either synchronously or asynchronously.
children.name: _Handler

children.comment: Returns a [Buffer] containing the command packet.
children.name: createRequest

children.comment:
Parses a [Buffer] containing the response to the command.
Returns a [Handler] if that handler should take over and
process subsequent packets from the server, otherwise the
result is returned in the [Future], either in one of the
Connection methods, or Transport.connect()
children.name: processResponse

children.comment:
Parses the response packet to recognise Ok and Error packets.
Returns an [OkPacket] if the packet was an Ok packet, throws
a [MySqlError] if it was an Error packet, or returns [:null:] 
if the packet has not been handled by this method.
children.name: checkResponse

children.comment: When [finished] is true, this handler has finished processing responses.
children.name: finished

children.comment: Create a [MySqlError] based on an error response from the mysql server
children.name: MySqlError._

children.comment:
Query is created by ConnectionPool.prepare(sql) and Transaction.prepare(sql). It holds
a prepared query. Set parameters on it using the square bracket operators.
children.name: Query

children.comment: Returns true if there was already a cached query which has been used.
children.name: _useCachedQuery

children.comment: Executes the query, returning a future [Results] object.
children.name: execute

children.comment:
Executes the query once for each set of [parameters], and returns a future list
of results, one for each set of parameters, that completes when the query has been executed.
children.name: executeMulti

children.comment: Get a current parameter value.
Set a parameter value.
Attempt to reuse a connection for a queued operation
children.name: _reuseConnection

children.comment:
Processes a handler, from sending the initial request to handling any packets returned from
mysql (unless [noResponse] is true).

Returns a future
children.name: processHandler

children.comment:
Maintains a pool of database connections. When queries are executed, if there is
a free connection it will be used, otherwise the query is queued until a connection is
free.
children.name: ConnectionPool

children.comment:
Attempts to continue using a connection. If the connection isn't managed
by this pool, or if the connection is already in use, nothing happens.

If there are operations which have been queued in this pool, starts
to execute that operation. 

Otherwise, nothing happens.

//TODO rename to something like processQueuedOperations??
children.name: _reuseConnection

children.comment:
Closes all open connections. 

WARNING: this will probably break things.
children.name: close

children.comment:
Executes the [sql] query as soon as a connection is available, returning
a [Future<Results>] that completes when the results are available.
children.name: query

children.comment: Pings the server. Returns a [Future] that completes when the server replies.
children.name: ping

children.comment:
Sends a debug message to the server. Returns a [Future] that completes
when the server replies.
children.name: debug

children.comment:
The future returned by [whenReady] fires when all queued operations in the pool
have completed, and the connection is free to be used again.
children.name: _waitUntilReady

children.comment:
Prepares a query with the given [sql]. Returns a [Future<Query>] that
completes when the query has been prepared.
children.name: prepare

children.comment:
Starts a transaction. Returns a [Future<Transaction>] that completes
when the transaction has been started. If [consistent] is true, the
transaction is started with consistent snapshot.
children.name: startTransaction

children.comment:
Prepares and executes the [sql] with the given list of [parameters].
Returns a [Future<Results>] that completes when the query has been
executed.
children.name: prepareExecute

children.comment:
Creates a [ConnectionPool]. When connections are required they will connect to the
[db] on the given [host] and [port], using the [user] and [password]. The [max] number
of simultaneous connections can also be specified.
children.name: ConnectionPool

children.comment: Holds blob data, and can be created or accessed as either a [String] or a [List] of ints.
children.name: Blob

children.comment: Returns the value of the blob as a [String].
children.name: toString

children.comment: Returns the value of the blob as a list of bytes.
children.name: toBytes

children.comment: Create a [Blob] from a [string].
children.name: Blob.fromString

children.comment: Create a [Blob] from a list of [bytes].
children.name: Blob.fromBytes

children.comment:
This provides methods to read and write strings, lists and
various sized integers on a buffer (implemented as an integer list).

The ints in the backing list must all be 8-bit values. If larger values are
entered, behaviour is undefined.

As per mysql spec, numbers here are all unsigned.
Which makes things much easier.
children.name: _Buffer

children.comment: Returns true if more data can be read from the buffer, false otherwise.
children.name: canReadMore

children.comment:
Reads up to [count] bytes from the [socket] into the buffer.
Returns the number of bytes read.
children.name: readFromSocket

children.comment:
Writes up to [count] bytes to the [socket] from the buffer.
Returns the number of bytes written.
children.name: writeToSocket

children.comment: Returns the int at the specified [index]
Sets the int at the specified [index] to the given [value]

Resets the read and write positions markers to the start of
the buffer
children.name: reset

children.comment: Moves the read marker to the given [position]
children.name: seek

children.comment: Moves the read marker forwards by the given [numberOfBytes]
children.name: skip

children.comment: Moves the write marker to the given [position]
children.name: seekWrite

children.comment: Moves the write marker forwards by the given [numberOfBytes]
children.name: skipWrite

children.comment: Fills the next [numberOfBytes] with the given [value]
children.name: fill

children.comment:
Reads a null terminated list of ints from the buffer.
Returns the list of ints from the buffer, without the terminating zero
children.name: readNullTerminatedList

children.comment:
Writes a null terminated list of ints from the buffer. The given [list]
should not contain the terminating zero.
children.name: writeNullTerminatedList

children.comment:
Reads a null terminated string from the buffer.
Returns the string, without a terminating null.
children.name: readNullTerminatedString

children.comment:
Writes a null terminated string to the buffer.
The given [string] does not need to contain the terminating null.
children.name: writeNullTerminatedString

children.comment:
Reads a string from the buffer, terminating when the end of the
buffer is reached.
children.name: readStringToEnd

children.comment:
Writes a [string] to the buffer, without any length indicators or
terminating nulls.
children.name: writeString

children.comment: Reads a string of the given [length] from the buffer.
children.name: readString

children.comment:
Reads a length coded binary from the buffer. This is specified in the mysql docs.
It will read up to nine bytes from the stream, depending on the first byte.
Returns an unsigned integer.
children.name: readLengthCodedBinary

children.comment: Will write a length coded binary value, once implemented!
children.name: writeLengthCodedBinary

children.comment: Returns a length coded string, read from the buffer.
children.name: readLengthCodedString

children.comment: Returns a single byte, read from the buffer.
children.name: readByte

children.comment: Writes a single [byte] to the buffer.
children.name: writeByte

children.comment: Returns a 16-bit integer, read from the buffer
children.name: readInt16

children.comment: Writes a 16 bit [integer] to the buffer.
children.name: writeInt16

children.comment: Returns a 24-bit integer, read from the buffer.
children.name: readInt24

children.comment: Writes a 24 bit [integer] to the buffer.
children.name: writeInt24

children.comment: Returns a 32-bit integer, read from the buffer.
children.name: readInt32

children.comment: Writes a 32 bit [integer] to the buffer.
children.name: writeInt32

children.comment: Returns a 64-bit integer, read from the buffer.
children.name: readInt64

children.comment: Writes a 64 bit [integer] to the buffer.
children.name: writeInt64

children.comment: Returns a list of the given [numberOfBytes], read from the buffer.
children.name: readList

children.comment: Writes the give [list] of bytes to the buffer.
children.name: writeList

children.comment: Returns the size of the buffer
children.name: length

children.comment: Creates a [Buffer] of the given [size]
children.name: _Buffer

children.comment: Creates a [Buffer] with the given [list] as backing storage
children.name: _Buffer.fromList
